    "summary": "The Three Kingdoms Period (220–280 AD) was one of the most turbulent and romanticized eras in Chinese history — a time when the Han Empire fractured into three competing states: Wei (north), Shu Han (southwest), and Wu (southeast), each claiming legitimacy as the successor to the Han dynasty. The period opened with the effective collapse of Han central authority amid [[event:2836|the Yellow Turban Rebellion]] and the rise of warlords, and concluded with the unification of China under the Jin dynasty in 280. The pivotal [[event:2837|Battle of Red Cliffs]] (208 AD) — where Cao Cao's northern fleet was destroyed by the allied forces of Liu Bei and Sun Quan — cemented the division into three states.\n\nDespite the warfare and population decline (which was catastrophic — China's population may have fallen by a third or more), the Three Kingdoms period produced significant cultural achievements and technological innovations. The era's military strategists, particularly Zhuge Liang (chancellor of Shu Han), became legendary figures in Chinese culture. The historical novel 'Romance of the Three Kingdoms' (written in the 14th century) immortalized this period as China's equivalent of the Trojan War cycle — a foundational national epic mixing history with legend. The period's influence on Chinese literature, strategy games, and popular culture remains enormous to the present day.",
